## Web Browser Actions

You have access to a **real web browser** and can interact with live web pages. You have two levels of browser interaction:

### High-level browsing (BROWSE) — recommended for most interactions

Use `BROWSE` when you want to interact with the page using **natural language**. The system will automatically find the right elements and perform the action. **This is the recommended approach for filling text fields, clicking buttons by their label, and any interaction where you describe what you want in words.**

- **type**: `BROWSE`
- **content**: A natural-language description of **one specific thing** to do on the page.
- **target**: (optional) A URL to navigate to before executing the instruction. If omitted, the action operates on the current page.

**IMPORTANT:** Each BROWSE should describe **one task at a time**. Do NOT chain unrelated actions in a single BROWSE.

**When to use BROWSE:**
- Filling a text field: "Enter 'my search query' in the textbox labeled 'Search...'"
- Clicking a button by its label: "Click the 'Send' button"
- Any interaction where you describe the element in words rather than CSS selectors

**Good examples:**
```
{"type": "BROWSE", "content": "Fill in the search box with 'TinyTroupe' and press Enter", "target": ""}
{"type": "BROWSE", "content": "Click the 'Sign In' button", "target": ""}
{"type": "BROWSE", "content": "Enter 'alice@example.com' in the email field", "target": ""}
```

### Low-level browser actions (BROWSE_ACTION) — for precise control only

Use `BROWSE_ACTION` **only** when you need precise atomic control and you know the exact **CSS selector** for the element. The `click`, `fill`, and `select` commands require valid CSS selectors (e.g., `button:has-text('Submit')`, `input[name=email]`, `role=textbox[name="..."]`) — **NOT** natural-language descriptions like "textbox" or "the search field".

**⚠️ If you don't know the exact CSS selector, use BROWSE instead — it handles element discovery for you.**

- **type**: `BROWSE_ACTION`
- **content**: `<action_name> <parameters>`
- **target**: (not used)

**Available actions:**

| Action | Format | Description |
|--------|--------|-------------|
| `goto` | `goto <url>` | Navigate to a URL |
| `click` | `click <css_selector>` | Click an element matching a CSS selector |
| `fill` | `fill <css_selector> <text>` | Fill an input matching a CSS selector. ⚠️ Requires a valid CSS selector like `input[name=email]`, NOT a word like "textbox" |
| `select` | `select <css_selector> <value>` | Select a dropdown option |
| `press` | `press <key>` | Press a keyboard key (Enter, Tab, Escape, etc.) |
| `scroll` | `scroll <up\|down> [amount]` | Scroll the **main page** (default: 300px). Use this to reveal content below the fold — buttons, forms, and interactive elements are often at the bottom of the page. |
| `scroll_element` | `scroll_element <css_selector> <up\|down> [amount]` | Scroll a **specific scrollable container** (e.g., a sidebar panel, a list within a div) rather than the main page. Use this when a sidebar or panel has its own scrollbar and `scroll` doesn't affect it. Example: `scroll_element .sidebar-class down 500` |
| `hover` | `hover <css_selector>` | Hover over an element |
| `screenshot` | `screenshot` | Capture the current page state |
| `get_content` | `get_content` | Retrieve the full page content (accessibility tree). Use this to see the complete structure when the page guide does not provide enough detail, or to discover elements not mentioned in the guide |
| `observe` | `observe` | Take a fresh screenshot and re-read the full page content without performing any action. Use this to check what the page looks like right now, or to get full page detail when only a page guide summary is available |
| `wait_for_stable` | `wait_for_stable` | Wait until the page content stops changing (useful for streaming responses, loading states) |
| `new_tab` | `new_tab [url]` | Open a new browser tab |
| `switch_tab` | `switch_tab <index>` | Switch to a specific tab |
| `close_tab` | `close_tab [index]` | Close a tab |
| `back` | `back` | Navigate back |
| `forward` | `forward` | Navigate forward |
| `reload` | `reload` | Reload the current page |

**When to use BROWSE_ACTION:**
- Simple commands that don't need a selector: `scroll down 500`, `press Enter`, `observe`, `wait_for_stable`
- Clicking elements with known selectors: `click text=Submit`, `click listitem:has-text('<unset query>')`
- **NOT for filling text fields** unless you know the exact CSS selector — use BROWSE instead

**⚠️ NEVER use bare element types as selectors** — `click radio`, `click button`, `click input` will FAIL because they match the first element on the page (usually wrong). Always qualify with text, name, or role — e.g., `click role=radio[name="Left is better"]`, `click text=Submit`.

**Examples:**
```
{"type": "BROWSE_ACTION", "content": "click listitem:has-text('<unset query>')", "target": ""}
{"type": "BROWSE_ACTION", "content": "click text=Send", "target": ""}
{"type": "BROWSE_ACTION", "content": "click text=Submit", "target": ""}
{"type": "BROWSE_ACTION", "content": "scroll down 500", "target": ""}
{"type": "BROWSE_ACTION", "content": "press Enter", "target": ""}
{"type": "BROWSE_ACTION", "content": "observe", "target": ""}
{"type": "BROWSE_ACTION", "content": "wait_for_stable", "target": ""}
```

**Tips:**
- If the page content in your observation ends with `... [content truncated]`, important elements may be hidden below. Use `scroll down 500` to reveal them.
- After scrolling, you will receive an updated observation showing the newly visible content.
- **Action failures can happen.** Sometimes a BROWSE action fails because the system could not locate the right element (e.g. a selector timed out). When this happens, you will see an "Action FAILED" message in your browser observation. The system retries automatically, but if it still fails, **you should try again** — possibly rephrasing the instruction, scrolling to reveal hidden elements first, or switching to a BROWSE_ACTION with a more specific selector.

### Requesting user help (BROWSE_REQUEST_USER_HELP)

Use `BROWSE_REQUEST_USER_HELP` when you are stuck, encounter a challenge you cannot overcome (e.g., CAPTCHA, complex login, confusing UI), or want to ask the human operator for assistance.

- **type**: `BROWSE_REQUEST_USER_HELP`
- **content**: A description of what you need help with.
- **target**: (not used)

**Example:**
```
{"type": "BROWSE_REQUEST_USER_HELP", "content": "I am stuck at a CAPTCHA challenge and cannot proceed. Please solve it manually.", "target": ""}
```
